congressional supremacy guided the <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">United States</ENAMEX> through <ENAMEX TYPE="EVENT">World War</ENAMEX> II.
(<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Occasionally</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> declared war before sending <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">troops</ENAMEX>; mostly it didn't.)
But <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX>' military influence began to wane as <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">presidents</ENAMEX> grabbed more and
more power. The seminal event was the <ENAMEX TYPE="EVENT">Korean War</ENAMEX>, which <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">President</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Harry Truman</ENAMEX>
waged with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.N.</ENAMEX> approval and virtual silence from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX>. The shift continued
through <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Vietnam</ENAMEX> and the secret invasions of <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Cambodia</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Laos</ENAMEX>. In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1973</TIMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> reasserted itself by passing the <ENAMEX TYPE="LAW">War Powers Resolution</ENAMEX> over <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nixon</ENAMEX>'s
veto. Under the resolution (more commonly known as the "<ENAMEX TYPE="LAW">War Powers Act</ENAMEX>"), the
<ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">president</ENAMEX> has <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">90 days</TIMEX> to obtain congressional approval of a military action. If
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> does not vote aye, the <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">troops</ENAMEX> must come home.

